Rating: 4
This dish really doesn't need any more reviews, but I just can't resist adding accolades and suggestions. I made the recipe just as written except that I used sour cream (I am a low-carb person). I thought the spices were perfect. I know that using the whole chicken with skin and bones is more authentic and tasty, but I really did enjoy the boneless morsels. The skin got flabby and so actually became a negative thing. Next time I am going to buy chicken breasts and thighs, debone and skin them, discard the skin, retain the bones, cut the chicken into largish, bite-size pieces, and add the chicken meat and bones to the sauce. I'll remove the bones before serving. As some other reviewers have suggested, I will increase tomatoes and broth to make more fabulous sauce. I live alone, so I made the dish on Sunday night, took out enough for my supper, and refrigerated the remainder without the cashews and yogurt. On Wednesday night, when I heated up the last serving, I had run out of cashews. In their place, I added a tablespoon of Soynut Butter. It was pretty good. For my weeknight dinners, I was satisfied with a side dish of steamed broccoli and cauliflower. A glass of gewurtztraminer went very well. For company, and I do think this would be a marvelous company dish, I would add an Indian bread, a raita, a pilaf such as the spiced rice (on this site), and would punch up my cauliflower somehow. This simple, delicious recipe is a real gift to lovers of Indian food.

