Rating: 4
This is one of the most sumptuous, richest dishes I've made from a recipe. This is the kind of recipe I'll file and eventually memorize. It's very forgiving, can be made spicier in a second, and holds and re-heats well. One key thing here is really to cook the spices in with the vegetables and the chicken pieces before adding the tomatoes. I added part of another can for a bit more liquid, as well as a couple of more cloves of garlic and plenty of ginger, given that both of these mellow out with a long cooking. And I added some lime juice at the end for another burst of flavor. I'm not surprised that some people thought this was bland. Boneless, skinless anything is bland. I used all bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs, and this made for a really rich, delicious dish. The bones really help to add body to the sauce. For those who think this is too hot, more yogurt at the end would help. I'll continue to experiment, but it's a really tasty recipes as it is.

Rating: 4
This is a delicious and fool-proof recipe! I've never had a better curry dish, even at the best Indian restaurant. It uses common ingredients, and is easy to throw together. Changes that I made: 1. I used a combination of boneless, skinless breasts & thighs, cut into large chunks. 2. I used coconut milk instead of yoghurt. 3. I added two peeled potatoes cut into 1-inch chunks, 1/2 a small cut-up cauliflower and about 3/4 cup frozen peas 20 minutes before serving. This made it less saucy, and also made it a complete meal. I served it over jasmine rice. Regarding the reviewer who felt it had too much onion, note that you usually get more than 1 cup of chopped onion per 1 onion. The recipe calls for two cups -- use that measure, not 2 onions. I do not know why some found this to be bland -- I found it to be bursting with flavor. I thought the heat factor was perfect, but then, I was using basic store-bought curry powder (Shillings), not specialty or hot curry powder. Also, I used basic cayenne pepper. If you use different spices than the recipe calls for, you will get a different result. This truly is so good I would be proud to serve it to guests or bring it to a potluck!

